This is an improvement to GHC-105.  While the data is now stored and happy in AO, the old references still lurk in JIRA's database and have the potential to still affect performance.  We've successfully run the following SQL directly on affected databases and after a restart the affected JIRA projects are running fast:

{code:SQL}
DELETE FROM propertytext WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key ILIKE '%IssueCommitArray%');
DELETE FROM propertyentry WHERE property_key ILIKE '%IssueCommitArray%';
{code}
*always take a database backup before performing direct database manipulation

If it's possible, it would be great if the plugin could handle this sort of thing in an upgrade task.

[com.atlassian.jira.plugins.bitbucket.spi.bitbucket.impl.BitbucketCommunicator.getChangesets(SourceControlRepository, String, int)|https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/jira-bitbucket-connector/src/ff0eab80bdbf/src/main/java/com/atlassian/jira/plugins/bitbucket/spi/bitbucket/impl/BitbucketCommunicator.java#cl-136] tries to parse HTML responses (in case of error) from the bitbucket API.

The erroneous response in our case was:

{noformat}
<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xml:lang="en" lang="en">
<head>
  <title>Someone kicked over the bucket, sadface &mdash; Bitbucket</title>
  <meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" />
  <link rel="icon" href="//bitbucket.org/m/img/logo_new.png" type="image/png" />
</head>
<body>
  <div style="width:100%; text-align:center;">
    <img src="//bitbucket.org/m/img/500.png" width="798" height="366" style="margin:100px auto"
         alt="Oops! An error occurred. We've been notified and we'll look into the problem." />
  </div>

  <script>
  BB.gaqPush(
      ['_trackPageview'],
      ['atl._trackPageview']
  );

  (function () {
      var ga = document.createElement('script');
      ga.src = ('https:' == document.location.protocol ? 'https://ssl' : 'http://www') + '.google-analytics.com/ga.js';
      ga.setAttribute('async', 'true');
     document.documentElement.firstChild.appendChild(ga);
 }());
 </script>
</body>
</html>
{noformat}

com.atlassian.jira.plugins.bitbucket.spi.ExtendedResponseHandler.ExtendedResponse.isSuccessful() should be checked before trying to parse the getResponseString(). That test boils down to:

{code}
public boolean isSuccessful()
{
    int codeOrder = method.getStatusCode() / 100;
    return codeOrder == 2 || codeOrder ==  3;
}
{code}

*I don't think it's a good idea to escape here.* We've got the ChangeSet id, so we can at least link to bitbucket. We can then show that the retrieval of the ChangeSet's details failed and encourage the user to retry syncing (maybe allow him to sync/retrieve details straight from the source tab?). I'd change the return value of this method to a Map<String,Either<ResponseError,ChangeSet>> where the String is the ChangeSet id, or I'd probably split up the ChangeSet contract.
